ns":["Atenolol","Metoprolol","Propranolol","Carvedilol","Bisoprolol"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtenolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a beta-1 selective antagonist without significant direct vasodilatory action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is beta-1 selective and does not produce direct vasodilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E is non-selective for beta receptors and lacks intrinsic vasodilatory properties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarvedilol\u003C/strong\u003E causes vasodilation via additional alpha-1 adrenoceptor blockade in vascular smooth muscle, reducing peripheral resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is beta-1 selective and does not have direct vasodilatory effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Some beta adrenoceptor antagonists cause vasodilation through additional mechanisms such as alpha-1 blockade or nitric oxide release.","Carvedilol produces vasodilation by blocking alpha-1 adrenoceptors in vascular smooth muscle.","Nebivolol produces vasodilation by stimulating endothelial nitric oxide release.","Beta-1 selective agents without ancillary properties have minimal direct vasodilatory effect."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17023"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93646",